\layout Title

Modular Fractal Measures
\layout Author

Linas Vepstas <linas@linas.org>
\layout Date

12 October 2004 (updated 11 September 2006)
\layout Abstract

This breif note reviews a circle of topics connecting the derivative of
 the Minkowski question mark function, the so-clled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

multi-fractal measures
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

, the distribution of the Farey fractions, one-dimensional lattice models
 in physics, such as the Ising model, the Potts model and the Kac model,
 and the symmetries of the maps between the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

natural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 topologies that underly these objects.
 
\layout Abstract

The question of what it means to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

take the derivative of the question mark function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 is explored.
 The natural topology of one-dimensional lattice models is reviewed.
 It is conjectured that the derivative of the question mark may be the limiting
 behavior of a modular form.
 (Modular forms are analytic functions that are closely related to elliptic
 functions, and have a particular kind of modular group symmetry).
 
\layout Abstract

This document is mostly a research diary noting various results, and is
 haphazardly structured.
 
\layout Abstract

This paper is part of a set of chapters that explore the relationship between
 the real numbers, the modular group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

, and fractals.
