\layout Subsection

Measure theory
\layout Standard

In order to do statistical mechanics on this lattice, one will need to integrate
 over subsets of this set, or possibly integrate over all of the set.
 The problem now arises: how does one define an integral on this space?
\layout Standard

However, the machinery of measure theory forces a radical shift in the language,
 notation and concepts used to discuss the problem.
 First of all, one can no longer employ the idea that the space consists
 of a set of points.
 There is a reason for this: not every subset of of an uncountably-infinite
 set is "measurable".
 In fact, almost all subsets of an uncountably-infinite set are not measureable.
 So the very first step of measure theory is to throw away almost all subsets
 of the total space.
 One keeps only the measureable sets.
\layout Standard

How does one do this? Need to define a [[sigma algebra]] for this space.
 I am aware of several possible sigma-algebras for this space.
 I claim, without proof, that the algebra generated by the [[cylinder set]]s
 is the most "natural" for this problem.
 The reason for this will hopefully emerge later in the discussion.
 A homework problem might be to list as many different possible sigma algebras
 as possible for this space.
 A real bonus would be to prove that this list is a complete list.
 
\layout Standard

In this new language, the Hamiltonian takes on a new and very different
 appearance.
 It is no longer a function from points to the reals, but a function from
 elements of the sigma algebra to the reals.
 Intuitively, this "new" Hamilton can be visualized or intuited as the "average"
 of the old, classical Hamiltonian, the average taken over a certain subset
 of points.
 However, this intuition is dangerous, and can lead to errors: in particular,
 one has the chicken-and-egg problem of how to define the "average" of the
 old, classical Hamiltonian.
 The new Hamiltonian is different, and cannot be constructed from the old
 Hamiltonian.
 However, there is a way to prove that the new Hamiltonian is a faithful
 representation of the old one.
 If one has choosen one's sigma algebra wisely, then for every possible
 point in the old set, there is a sequence or [[filter (mathematics)|filter]]
 or [[net (mathematics)|net]] of elements of the sigma algebra that contain
 the old point, and the measure of the elements in this sequence decreases
 to zero.
 
\layout Standard

Suppose that the elements of this net are denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{n}$
\end_inset 

 for integer ''n''.
 The net is ordered so that 
\begin_inset Formula \mu(\sigma_{n})<\mu(\sigma_{k})

\end_inset 

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $n>k$
\end_inset 

.
 The "new" Hamiltonian is some function that assigns a real value to each
 
\begin_inset Formula \sigma_{n}

\end_inset 

.
 We can then say that the new and the old Hamiltonians are equal or equivalent
 when, for the "classical" point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p \in\sigma_{n} \quad\forall n\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}\]

\end_inset 

and
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{n \to\infty} \mu(\sigma_{n}) = 0\]

\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{n \to\infty} \frac{H(\sigma_{n})}{\mu(\sigma_{n})} = E_{p}\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula E_{p}

\end_inset 

 is the classical energy of the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 which the net is converging to.
 Again: to be clear: the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 is a possible configuration of the lattice model; each and every point
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 corresponds to an infinite string in two letters, and vice-versa, in one-to-one
 correspondence.
 If a net can be found for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

, and the above relationship holds for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

, and it holds for all possible nets to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

, then we can honestly and truthfully insists that the "new" and the "old"
 Hamiltonians "are the same".
\layout Standard

The above sets up a rigorous and mathematically precise vocabulary for the
 further discussion of the problem.
